un, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Reviers","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Altered form of French   Riviere   and possibly also of Dutch   Revier  .","History: This surname is listed in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors."],"variants":[{"name":"Riviere","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Pierre, Camille, Firmin, Hermite, Lucien, Monique, Stephane.","French (<b>Rivière</b>): topographic name for someone who lived by the bank of a river or shore of a lake, from Old French <i>riviere</i> ‘river, shore’ (originally meaning ‘riverbank’, from Latin <i>riparia</i>); or a habitational name from any of various places called (La) Rivière, for example in Indre-et-Loire and Pas-de-Calais. Compare   Lariviere   1 and 2.","History: Joseph Rivière from Bordeaux in Gironde, France, married Félicité Audet in Carleton, QC, in 1795."]}]},{"name":"Maud","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval vernacular form of   Matilda .  This form was characteristically Low German (i.e. including medieval Dutch and Flemish). The wife of  William the Conqueror , who bore this name, was the daughter of  Baldwin , Count of Flanders. In Flemish and Dutch the letter <i>-t-</i> was generally lost when it occurred between vowels, giving forms such as <i>Ma(h)auld</i>. <i>Maud</i> or <i>Matilda</i> was also the name of the daughter (  1102–67 ) of  Henry I  of England; she was married early in life to the Holy Roman Emperor  Henry V , and later disputed the throne of England with her cousin  Stephen . In  1128  she married  Geoffrey , Count of Anjou. A medieval chronicler commented, ‘she was a good woman, but she had little bliss with him’. The name <i>Maud</i> became quite common in England in the 19th century, when its popularity was influenced in part by  Tennyson's  poem Maud, published in  1855 , but has not been much used since the early decades of the 20th century."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Maud de Reviers was born about 1138, in Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom. She had at least 1 son with Ralph Avenal. She died about 1165, in Bicknor, Kent, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 29."},"et":{"about 1138–about 1165":"umbes 1138–umbes 1165","1128–1178":"1128–1178","1160–Male":"1160–Surnud","1138–1165":"1138–1165","1128":"1128","1138":"1138","about 1138":"umbes 1138","1178":"1178","1165":"1165","about 1165":"umbes 1165","1160":"1160","Derbyshire, England":"Derbyshire, England","Hocknorton, Oxfordshire, England":"Oxfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Bicknor, Hollingbourn, Kent, England":"Bicknor, Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1138–about 1165":"noin 1138–noin 1165","1128–1178":"1128–1178","1160–Male":"1160–Kuollut","1138–1165":"1138–1165","1128":"1128","1138":"1138","about 1138":"noin 1138","1178":"1178","1165":"1165","about 1165":"noin 1165","1160":"1160","Derbyshire, England":"Derbyshire, England","Hocknorton, Oxfordshire, England":"Oxfordshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Bicknor, Hollingbourn, Kent, England":"Bicknor, Kent, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"about 1138–about 1165":"environ 1138–environ 1165","1128–1178":"1128–1178","1160–Male":"1160–Décédé","1138–1165":"1138–1165","1128":"1128","1138":"1138","about 1138":"environ 1138","1178":"1178","1165":"1165","about 1165":"environ 1165","1160":"1160","Derbyshire, England":"Derbyshire, Angleterre","Hocknorton, Oxfordshire, England":"Oxfordshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Bicknor, Hollingbourn, Kent, England":"Bicknor, Kent, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Maud de Reviers est née environ 1138, à 